Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.00,0:00:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Under the cover of darkness,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.00,0:00:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the world lies hidden from view.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.00,0:00:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Without light, I've no idea what lies beyond my immediate surroundings.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.00,0:00:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I'm closed in, enveloped on all sides
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.00,0:00:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,by the unknown.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.00,0:00:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,For much of human history,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.00,0:00:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,when the sun went down and the dark set in,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.00,0:00:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we were at the mercy of the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.00,0:00:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But over the centuries,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.00,0:00:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we've developed our own sources of illumination.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.00,0:01:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,We've lit our homes, our streets, our cities,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.00,0:01:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and doing so, we've banished the darkness into the shadows.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.00,0:01:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And just as we've used light to illuminate our world,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.00,0:01:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the more we've discovered about light's properties,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.00,0:01:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the more of the Universe it's shown us.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.00,0:01:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,We've seen into the depths of space...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.00,0:01:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..and back to the beginning of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.00,0:01:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But as we've looked deeper,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.00,0:02:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we've come to realise how little we've seen
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.00,0:02:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and that the cosmos's greatest mysteries
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.00,0:02:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,remain hidden in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.00,0:02:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Light and dark is essentially the story
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.00,0:02:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,of everything we know
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.10,0:02:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and everything we don't know about our Universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.00,0:02:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it all begins with light.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.00,0:02:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's such an integral part of the way we perceive the world,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.00,0:02:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's easy to take it for granted.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.00,0:03:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But for centuries, understanding what light really is
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.00,0:03:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,has been one of science's most enduring questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.00,0:03:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The first steps toward understanding the properties of light
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.00,0:03:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,were made in the third century BC
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.00,0:03:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,by the renowned Greek mathematician Euclid.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.00,0:03:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He did it by thinking about something so obvious,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.00,0:03:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,most of us don't give it any thought at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.00,0:03:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Placing the tiny chair very close to the camera
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.00,0:03:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,produces a large image on the retina,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.00,0:03:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and because we're not used to seeing tiny chairs in everyday life,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.00,0:03:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,our brains are tricked into thinking
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.00,0:03:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's a normal-sized chair in the middle of the room.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.00,0:03:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The reason this illusion works at all
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.00,0:04:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is because, to judge distances,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.00,0:04:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,our brains rely on a simple fact -
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.00,0:04:06.20,English1,,0,0,0,,the further away things are
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.20,0:04:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the smaller they appear to the eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.00,0:04:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it was by focusing on exactly why
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.00,0:04:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,distant objects could appear the same size
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.00,0:04:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,as much smaller ones closer up.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.00,0:04:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,...that led Euclid to discover of one of light's most fundamental properties.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.00,0:04:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Obviously the London Eye is much bigger than my fingers, I know that,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.00,0:04:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and yet to me they look the same size.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.00,0:04:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So, how do we explain this?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.00,0:04:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Well, Euclid came up with an elegant solution.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.00,0:05:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,For my finger to appear at the top of the wheel,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.00,0:05:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,my eye, my finger and the top of the wheel
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.00,0:05:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,must all lie on the same line.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.00,0:05:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But Euclid's insight didn't just explain the tricks of perspective,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.00,0:05:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it revealed a basic truth about light itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.00,0:05:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Euclid had discovered that light travels in straight lines
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.00,0:05:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Realising how it travels
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.00,0:05:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,marks the beginning of our scientific understanding of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.00,0:05:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it also meant that if we could divert it from its straight-line path,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.00,0:05:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we could change the way we see the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.00,0:06:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But that leap wouldn't happen for another 2,000 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.00,0:06:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was eventually made in Renaissance Italy
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.00,0:06:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,by one of the founding fathers of modern science.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.00,0:06:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In the summer of 1609,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.00,0:06:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo Galilei made the short but fateful journey
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.00,0:06:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,from his home in Padua to Venice,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.00,0:06:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,capital of the Venetian Republic.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.00,0:06:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo had flame-red hair, a full beard,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.00,0:06:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and was well-known for his love of fine wines and generous hospitality,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.00,0:06:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and also for his anti-establishment views.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.00,0:06:53.50,English1,,0,0,0,,By this time, he'd also built up a reputation
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.50,0:06:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,as a natural philosopher and mathematician
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.00,0:07:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and he was regarded as a valuable asset to the Venetian Republic
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.00,0:07:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But although, as a professor, he had a regular income,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.00,0:07:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo was never far from financial troubles.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.00,0:07:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,When his father died in 1591,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.00,0:07:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo, the eldest of four surviving siblings,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.00,0:07:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,became the head of the household
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.00,0:07:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and, effectively, took on responsibility for supporting his brother,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.00,0:07:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a poor itinerant musician,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.00,0:07:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and for paying his sisters' dowries.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.00,0:07:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,By the time he came to Venice,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.00,0:07:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he still owed a significant amount of money to his two brothers in law
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.00,0:07:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and so was always on the lookout for a money-making scheme.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.00,0:07:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,That summer,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.00,0:07:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Venice was abuzz with rumours of a device
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.00,0:07:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that appeared to do the impossible...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.00,0:07:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..a Dutch spyglass
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.00,0:07:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that could bring distant objects closer.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.00,0:08:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was just opportunity Galileo was looking for.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.00,0:08:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Back in the 17th Century,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.00,0:08:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the spyglass was cutting-edge technology
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.00,0:08:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the details of how it worked were a closely-guarded secret.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.00,0:08:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,All Galileo knew was that it consisted of two lenses arranged in a tube,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.00,0:08:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and so when he developed his own, he kept it very secret, as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.00,0:08:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But we do know from a shopping list
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.00,0:08:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that he got his glass from the small island of Murano, out in the lagoon,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.00,0:08:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and because no tools existed, he had to improvise,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.00,0:08:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,for instance, buying an artillery ball
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.00,0:08:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to grind the curved surfaces of the lenses.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.00,0:08:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It had been known since the first spectacles were produced,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.00,0:08:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in the middle of the 13th century,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.00,0:09:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that glass had the strange property of bending light.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.00,0:09:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But unlike spectacles,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.00,0:09:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the spyglass, an early telescope,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.00,0:09:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,required a combination of lenses
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.00,0:09:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in a very specific arrangement
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.00,0:09:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is how Galileo's telescope works.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.00,0:09:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Rays of light come in from a distant object
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.00,0:09:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so they're almost parallel where they meet his first lens.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.00,0:09:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is the objective lens, and it's plano-convex,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.00,0:09:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which means it's flat on one side and curved on the other.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.00,0:09:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's the sort of lens used to treat long-sightedness
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.00,0:09:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What it does is bend the rays of light towards each other
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.00,0:09:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so that they would meet at a point.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.00,0:09:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But before this focal point,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.00,0:09:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo places his second lens, the ocular lens, which is plano-concave,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.00,0:09:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and this bends the rays of light back out again
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.00,0:09:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so they emerge parallel, where they enter the eye,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.00,0:10:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and then the eye's lens focuses them on the retina.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.00,0:10:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now the magnification of a telescope depends on the ratio
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.00,0:10:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,of the focal lengths of the two lenses -
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.00,0:10:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the distances F1 and F2.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.00,0:10:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The difficulty for Galileo
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.00,0:10:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was grinding down the convex surface of his objective lens
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.00,0:10:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to make it as shallow as possible
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.00,0:10:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in order to maximise the length F1,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.00,0:10:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because the longer he could make that,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.00,0:10:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the greater the magnification of his telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.00,0:10:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Produced in just a few weeks,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.00,0:10:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo's telescope had a magnification of eight times
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.00,0:10:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and was far more powerful than the original spyglass.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.00,0:10:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,All he needed to do now
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.00,0:10:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was cash in on his new invention.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.00,0:10:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Ever the showman, on the 21st August, 1609,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.00,0:10:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo climbed one of the city s bell towers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.00,0:10:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,BELLS CHIME
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.00,0:11:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,LIFT MUZAK: "The Girl from Ipanema"
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.00,0:11:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Obviously, he would've used the stairs!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.00,0:11:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,At the top, in front of an assembled group of Venetian noblemen and senators,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.00,0:11:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo demonstrated his telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.00,0:11:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was a sensation.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.00,0:11:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Using it, the Venetians would be able to see approaching ships
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.00,0:11:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,two hours earlier than with naked eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.00,0:11:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The military and economic advantage of knowing who was sailing over the horizon
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.00,0:11:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was lost on no-one watching that day.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.00,0:11:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Three days later, as a grand gesture,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.00,0:12:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo presented his telescope to the duke as a gift.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.00,0:12:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In return, he was guaranteed his job for life,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.00,0:12:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,at double his salary.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.00,0:12:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,With his finances now secure,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.00,0:12:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo went on to develop a more powerful telescope,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.00,0:12:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and with it, use the ability to bend light
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.00,0:12:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to change our perspective on the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.00,0:12:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is the book Galileo published in 1610.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.00,0:12:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's called "Sidereus Nuncius",
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.00,0:12:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which in Latin means "The Starry Messenger".
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.00,0:12:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In it, he recorded his first observations of the night sky
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.00,0:12:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the first anyone had ever made
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.00,0:12:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,using anything other than the naked eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.00,0:12:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Today, it's hard to imagine
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.00,0:13:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,how anything contained in this little book was controversial,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.00,0:13:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but you have to remember that when it was written,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.00,0:13:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the nature of heavens was thought to be knowable only to God
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.00,0:13:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the Earth was considered to be at the centre of the Universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.00,0:13:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,These are his drawings of the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.00,0:13:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Since ancient times, all heavenly bodies were thought to be perfect spheres,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.00,0:13:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but with his telescope, Galileo saw texture in the surface of the moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.00,0:13:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,deep craters and mountains
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.00,0:13:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that, from the shadows they cast across the lunar surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.00,0:13:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he estimated to be some six kilometres tall.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.00,0:13:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,As well as showing the heavens to be imperfect...
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.00,0:13:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..his telescope began to uncover their true extent,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.00,0:14:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,revealing ten-times more stars
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.00,0:14:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,than are visible to the naked eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.00,0:14:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And in the final chapters,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.00,0:14:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo reports the discovery of four stars
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.00,0:14:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that appeared to form a straight line
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.00,0:14:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,near the planet Jupiter.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.00,0:14:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,His drawings show how their positions change from night to night.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.00,0:14:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Although they moved, they always did so along the same straight line,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.00,0:14:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and from that, Galileo deduced that they had to be orbiting Jupiter.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.00,0:14:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,They weren't stars at all, they were moons.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.00,0:14:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Through his telescope,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.00,0:14:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo had seen evidence
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.00,0:14:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that overturned the accepted dogma
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.00,0:14:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that the Earth was the fulcrum
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.00,0:14:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,about which everything in the Universe revolved.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.00,0:14:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Seeing moons in orbit around Jupiter
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.00,0:14:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,meant that not everything went round the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.00,0:15:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So, far from being the centre of the Universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.00,0:15:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the Earth was just another planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.00,0:15:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The telescope had allowed Galileo
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.00,0:15:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to glimpse the true nature of the cosmos
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.00,0:15:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and our place within it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.00,0:15:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But this way of manipulating light
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.00,0:15:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,had another powerful application,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.00,0:15:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,one that would allow us to see into another world.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.00,0:15:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,BELLS CHIME
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.00,0:15:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In 17th-century London,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.00,0:15:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,one of the most prominent scientists of the age
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.00,0:16:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was using lenses in a very different way.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.00,0:16:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Robert Hooke had taken the basic principle of the telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.00,0:16:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and used it to build a microscope.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.00,0:16:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo uses the telescope to discover a new world in the heavens,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.00,0:16:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and Hooke uses the microscope to discover a new world
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.00,0:16:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in the very, very small.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.00,0:16:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But there's a difference, because what Galileo had presented
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.00,0:16:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was a world that was bigger and more plentiful,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.00,0:16:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but it was a world that people were at least vaguely familiar with
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.00,0:16:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because you can look up in the sky and see the stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.00,0:16:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,whereas the world that Hooke presented
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.00,0:16:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was really something spectacular and new.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.00,0:16:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was a world inside the tiniest particles of matter
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.00,0:17:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that no-one had ever imagined to be there before.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.00,0:17:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,People didn't even realise
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.00,0:17:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that there was a microscopic world there to reveal.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.00,0:17:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke trained his microscope
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.00,0:17:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,on a huge range of materials and living things.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.00,0:17:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But it was his drawings of the exquisite detail he saw in the bodies of insects
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.00,0:17:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that would become famous.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.00,0:17:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Up here, you can see a human flea, Pulex irritans, a very tiny creature,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.00,0:17:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and here we've got the plate from "Micrographia",
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.00,0:17:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which is a huge image of the flea that Hooke produced,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.00,0:17:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and it's really something spectacular.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.00,0:17:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This would've folded out in the book, so it was really very large.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.00,0:17:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Some people said it was as big as a cat.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.00,0:17:53.50,English1,,0,0,0,,It's a work of art, really. I mean,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.50,0:17:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,there's so much intricate detail in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.00,0:17:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It is, and there was nothing like it before Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.00,0:18:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,They really were unprecedented
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.00,0:18:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the shading and the quality of the images is just superb.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.00,0:18:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it's accurate. I mean, it's... It is, it's absolutely accurate
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.00,0:18:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I was looking yesterday at images of, er, photographs of the flea and, er, there's really -
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.00,0:18:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,made with an electron microscope -
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.00,0:18:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and there's really nothing to chose between Hooke and, er,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.00,0:18:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the current images.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.00,0:18:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is an image of the compound eye of a fly,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.00,0:18:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which Hooke shows in amazing detail for the first time.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.00,0:18:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is an image of the foot of a fly.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.00,0:18:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke shows you the foot has little spikes in it
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.00,0:18:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that allow it to clasp into the pores on a surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.00,0:18:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This image looks less interesting, less intricate than the others
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.00,0:18:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It doesn't look terribly interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.00,0:18:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but, actually, it's really quite a profound picture,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.00,0:18:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because what Hooke is looking at here is a very thin slice of cork,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.00,0:18:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which he cut with a penknife,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.00,0:19:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and he's looking at the little individual components that make it up.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.00,0:19:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And he calls them pores, and then he calls them caverns,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.00,0:19:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he calls them boxes and then he calls them cells,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.00,0:19:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and cell, of course, is the term that stuck.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.00,0:19:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,These are the little constituent parts, not just of cork, but of all living things,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.00,0:19:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and so it's a profoundly important discovery
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.00,0:19:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and a name that has become standard in biology.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.00,0:19:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Using glass to bend light
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.00,0:19:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,revealed our true place in the Universe...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.00,0:20:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..and the intricate architecture of the microscopic world.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.00,0:20:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The more we looked,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.00,0:20:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the more we saw.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.00,0:20:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,With each new insight into the nature of light
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.00,0:20:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,came a fresh understanding of the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:34.00,0:20:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And the next discovery
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.00,0:20:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,would take us far further...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.00,0:20:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..and enable us to read the story of the stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.00,0:21:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it began with something Hooke had glimpsed through his microscope.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.00,0:21:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is Robert Hooke's book The Micrographia,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.00,0:21:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,published in 1664,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.00,0:21:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,350 years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.00,0:21:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's full of...
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.00,0:21:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..his famous diagrams.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.00,0:21:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Here's his picture of the flea.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.00,0:21:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's incredible seeing it in its original form.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.00,0:21:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It really is the size of a cat!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.00,0:21:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,These images really captured the public imagination and they made the book a sensation,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.00,0:21:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but for me, The Micrographia is about much more than that.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.00,0:21:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The chapter that interests me as a physicist
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.00,0:21:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is one that contains hardly any images at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.00,0:21:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And it's this one here -
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.00,0:21:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,"Of the Colours observable
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.00,0:21:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,"in Muscovy Glass, and other thin Bodies".
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.00,0:21:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Here Hooke describes the iridescent patterns of rainbow colours
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.00,0:21:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he sees through his microscope
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.00,0:22:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,as light passes through thin materials,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.00,0:22:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,like soap bubbles and Muscovy-glass,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.00,0:22:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a silicate mineral that's made up of lots of thin layers.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.00,0:22:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,At the time, it was thought that white light like sunlight, was pure,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.00,0:22:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that it came directly from God
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.00,0:22:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and so Hooke concluded that the colours he was seeing
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.00,0:22:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,must have somehow been added to the light,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.00,0:22:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that they were effectively created
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.00,0:22:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,as the light passed through the materials.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.00,0:22:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But Hooke's theory about coloured light
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.00,0:22:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was about to be challenged by his greatest rival.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.00,0:22:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton is one of the world's most revered scientists...
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.00,0:22:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..best known for his theory of universal gravitation.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.00,0:23:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And just like his laws of gravity,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.00,0:23:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's discoveries about the nature of light
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.00,0:23:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,are among his most celebrated achievements.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.00,0:23:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But the story of how that work began is much less familiar,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.00,0:23:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And this time, there was no fruit involved.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.00,0:23:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is Stourbridge Common,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.00,0:23:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a sleepy riverside meadow on the banks of the River Cam.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.00,0:23:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But when Newton's visited in 1664, it would've been very different.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.00,0:23:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,For over 700 years, every September this place would be transformed
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.00,0:23:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,into what was, at its height, the largest fair in Europe.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.00,0:23:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,For several weeks each year, people would descend on the common
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.00,0:23:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,for an annual festival of commerce and debauchery.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.00,0:23:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,DOGS BARK SHOUTING
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.00,0:24:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,SWORDS CLASH APPLAUSE
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.00,0:24:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This whole common would've been packed with make-shift stalls
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.00,0:24:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,farming produce, brandy houses, goldsmiths, silk merchants.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.00,0:24:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,There'd have been slack-rope dancing, puppet shows, music,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.00,0:24:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,temptations of every kind,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.00,0:24:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,packed into row upon row of wooden booths and tents.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.00,0:24:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Stourbridge Fair was a place you could buy anything you could imagine,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.00,0:24:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but when Newton came here, it's said he bought just one thing -
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.00,0:24:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a prism.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.00,0:24:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He bought it because it performed the same magic
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.00,0:24:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke had seen with his microscope.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.00,0:25:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton would later write that, using his new purchase,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.00,0:25:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he would "try the celebrated phenomena of colours"...
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.00,0:25:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..a rather understated introduction
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.00,0:25:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to work that would produce one of the most profound insights into the nature of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.00,0:25:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton devised an ingenious experiment
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.00,0:25:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to discover precisely how these rainbow colours were produced
Dialogue: 0,0:25:36.00,0:25:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and to put Hooke's theory -
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.00,0:25:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that they were created by the prism itself - to the test.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.00,0:25:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is Newton's own drawing of what he called his "Crucial Experiment".
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.00,0:25:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In it, he arranged a prism so that sunlight -
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.00,0:26:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,coming in from a small hole he'd made in the shutters of his bedroom window -
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.00,0:26:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,passed through it and projected coloured light onto a screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.00,0:26:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Well, here's my light source
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.00,0:26:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and here's my prism
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.00,0:26:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which, if I arrange carefully,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.00,0:26:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I can get projected onto the back pillar.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.00,0:26:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Of course, none of this was new
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.00,0:26:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,People knew that prisms produced coloured light,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.00,0:26:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but what Newton did next had never been done before.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.00,0:26:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He first isolated one of the colours using a slit,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.00,0:26:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so in this case,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.00,0:26:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the orange light.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.00,0:26:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He then passed that orange light through a second prism.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.00,0:26:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, if Hooke was right,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.00,0:26:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,then this prism should add the other colours to the orange
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.00,0:26:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and reproduce the rainbow.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.00,0:27:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But all Newton saw was orange light.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.00,0:27:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The prism wasn't adding any extra colour.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.00,0:27:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He concluded that the colours must be contained in the white light in the first place,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.00,0:27:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that white light wasn't pure
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.00,0:27:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and prisms don't add anything to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.00,0:27:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Instead, they split it up into its constituent parts.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.00,0:27:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton named the colours that make up white light
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.00,0:27:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,"the spectrum",
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.00,0:27:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and when this discovery was combined with the telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.00,0:27:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it would show us something remarkable.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.00,0:27:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The spectrum would reveal
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.00,0:27:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,precisely what it was we were looking at out in space
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.00,0:27:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is a spectroscope.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.00,0:27:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,As sunlight comes in, it's broken up into its constituent colours
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.00,0:27:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and spread out much more finely than you'd get with a simple prism.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.00,0:27:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, with this camera,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.00,0:27:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I should be able to show you what I can see.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.00,0:28:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I'll just check that it's working.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.00,0:28:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Yes. OK.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.00,0:28:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,When scientists first did this in the middle of the 19th century...
Dialogue: 0,0:28:11.00,0:28:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I'm placing the spectroscope on top.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.00,0:28:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..they saw something completely unexpected.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.00,0:28:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,You can see the colours of the spectrum as Newton would've seen them,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.00,0:28:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but if you look more closely, you can see something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.00,0:28:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's not continuous,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.00,0:28:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's broken up by lots of thin black lines.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.00,0:28:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,These are gaps in the spectrum.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.00,0:28:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was soon realised that these gaps
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.00,0:28:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,were due to atoms in the outer atmosphere of the sun
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.00,0:28:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,absorbing certain wavelengths of light coming from its interior,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.00,0:28:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and that they could be used
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.00,0:28:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to work out the chemical composition of the sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.00,0:29:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Every element absorbs a unique pattern of wavelengths -
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.00,0:29:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,an optical fingerprint
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.00,0:29:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that can be used to determine the chemicals
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.00,0:29:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that make up any bright object you can see in the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.00,0:29:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And in Rome,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.00,0:29:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,one man was using this technique to study light
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.00,0:29:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,whose origins lay far beyond the sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.00,0:29:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Father Angelo Secchi was no ordinary priest.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.00,0:29:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He was charismatic and viewed as something of a heretic by his fellow Jesuits.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.00,0:29:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,That's because he was also a professor of physics,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.00,0:29:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,with a evangelical passion for astronomy.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.00,0:29:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In 1852,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:54.00,0:29:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Secchi was appointed Director of the Vatican Observatory.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.00,0:30:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Within a year, he'd built a new observatory
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.00,0:30:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,on the roof of St Ignatius Church, in the heart of the city.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.00,0:30:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,At the time, most astronomers were interested in mapping the positions of the stars
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.00,0:30:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and charting their motions across the heavens.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.00,0:30:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But Secchi was different.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.00,0:30:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,He wanted to know what they actually were.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:23.00,0:30:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So from his vantage point, high above the streets of the Eternal City,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.00,0:30:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,he began to meticulously analyse their light.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.00,0:30:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Fitting a spectroscope to the observatory's telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.00,0:30:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Father Secchi laboriously recorded the spectra
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.00,0:30:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,of more than 4,000 stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.00,0:31:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is Secchi's book "Le Stelle", The Stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.00,0:31:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which he published in 1877.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.00,0:31:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And flicking through it,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.00,0:31:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,you can see many of the observations that he made.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.00,0:31:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This one in particular is interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.00,0:31:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It shows some of the spectra he recorded.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.00,0:31:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The top one here is from the sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.00,0:31:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but the second one is starlight
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.00,0:31:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's from Sirius A, the Dog Star,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.00,0:31:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which is the brightest star in the night sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.00,0:31:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's 8.6 light years from Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.00,0:31:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and over 20 times as luminous as the sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.00,0:31:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,You can see from its spectrum this clear sequence of bands,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:48.00,0:31:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which is the signature of hydrogen,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.00,0:31:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because it's a relatively young star.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.00,0:32:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The Universe's hottest, brightest stars
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.00,0:32:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,have spectra rich in the two lightest elements -
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.00,0:32:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,hydrogen and helium.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.00,0:32:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But as they age, they cool,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.00,0:32:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and their spectra reveal the presence of many heavier elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.00,0:32:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This third one is from the star Betelgeuse,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.00,0:32:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which is a red supergiant.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.00,0:32:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's near the end of its life
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.00,0:32:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and so you can see from the many bands here
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.00,0:32:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that it's composed of lots of different elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.00,0:32:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What's remarkable about this image is that,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.00,0:32:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I mean, it really is one of the key moments in the history of astronomy,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.00,0:32:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that we can learn so much about what distant stars are made of
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.00,0:32:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,just by examining their light.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.00,0:33:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But because Secchi had catalogued the spectra of so many stars of different ages,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.00,0:33:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,his observations led to something even more profound -
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.00,0:33:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that by analysing starlight,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.00,0:33:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we can determine the stars' life cycles...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:27.00,0:33:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..when they were born...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.00,0:33:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..and when they'll die.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.00,0:33:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Understanding the spectrum
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.00,0:33:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,had allowed us to read the story of the stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.00,0:33:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's quite incredible to think
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.00,0:33:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that what began as a simple experiment in a darkened room
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.00,0:34:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,could reveal so much about the Universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.00,0:34:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that the scant light from those tiny points in the night sky
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.00,0:34:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,could contain within it the epic drama of the heavens.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.00,0:34:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But that wasn't all the spectrum could tell us.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.00,0:34:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Today,We know that it's made up of light of many different wavelengths,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.00,0:34:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and that those wavelengths extend way beyond the range we can see
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.00,0:34:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The spectrum, from the longest wavelengths used in radio communications,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.00,0:34:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to the very shortest wavelength gamma rays,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.00,0:34:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,covers a range of 30 orders of magnitude.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.00,0:34:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The longest are 1-followed-by-30-zeros
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.00,0:34:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,bigger than the shortest.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:54.00,0:34:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,That's the same as a spread in range of weights
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.00,0:35:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,from that of a single grain of sand
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.00,0:35:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to the weight of all the water in all the oceans on the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.00,0:35:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And within that vast spread,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.00,0:35:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,visible light - the frequencies we can see -
Dialogue: 0,0:35:09.00,0:35:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,covers a factor of just two.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.00,0:35:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,That's the same as the difference in weight
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.00,0:35:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,between this pebble and one twice its size.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.00,0:35:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Are we all set, Doctor? Yes, I think so.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:28.00,0:35:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And throughout the 20th century,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.00,0:35:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,opening our eyes to the full spectrum
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.00,0:35:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,revealed even more of the Universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.00,0:35:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,If you had infrared eyes, here's how the sky would look.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.00,0:35:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Infrared allowed us to see the Universe's coolest stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.00,0:35:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,while radio telescopes,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.00,0:35:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,sensitive to the longest wavelengths,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.00,0:35:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,revealed a cosmos in turmoil...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.00,0:35:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's the violent events that are picked up,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:36:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,exploded stars and galaxies.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.00,0:36:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..and satellites have scoured the heavens
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.00,0:36:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,for short-wavelength ultra violet.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.00,0:36:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The OAO picks the ultra-violet light from hot stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.00,0:36:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which the atmosphere cuts off from ground telescopes.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.00,0:36:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And here's the very latest window - gamma rays -
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.00,0:36:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which are like very energetic x-rays.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:23.00,0:36:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Seeing beyond the visible
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.00,0:36:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,has allowed us to peer deep into the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.00,0:36:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I was cock-a-hoop about this.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:31.00,0:36:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I, too, was wildly excited when I heard of this discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:42.00,0:36:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But the very fact that light had proved such a useful tool
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.00,0:36:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,for exploring the Universe
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.00,0:36:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,depended on one of its most mysterious properties.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.00,0:36:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Light behaves like a wave,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.00,0:36:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but if it is a wave, what is it a wave in?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.00,0:37:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Waves are carried across the ocean by the water.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.00,0:37:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The sound you can hear now is due to waves in the air.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.00,0:37:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In the vacuum of space, there is no air
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.00,0:37:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so there is no sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.00,0:37:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But the reason you can see me is because I'm lit by sunlight
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.00,0:37:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that has travelled 150 million kilometres
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.00,0:37:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,through empty space.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.00,0:37:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So, what is light,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.00,0:37:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and how can you have a wave in nothing?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:25.00,0:37:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Answering that question would not only reveal what light is,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.00,0:37:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it would ultimately allow us to glimpse
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.00,0:37:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the beginning of the Universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.00,0:37:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And the first part of the solution
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.00,0:37:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was a discovery that challenged our most basic assumptions
Dialogue: 0,0:37:53.00,0:37:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,about how we see the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.00,0:38:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,To our eyes, light appears to be everywhere
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.00,0:38:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,instantaneously.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.00,0:38:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,When I look out at the view, there seems to be no time lag,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.00,0:38:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,no delay, while I wait for the light to reach me.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.00,0:38:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But towards the end of the 17th century,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.00,0:38:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it was discovered that our senses are mistaken.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.00,0:38:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In 1672, the Danish astronomer Ole Romer arrived in Paris
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.00,0:38:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to begin work at the city's observatory
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.00,0:38:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and to continue his observations of the moons of Jupiter.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.00,0:38:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,For more than a decade
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.00,0:38:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Giovanni Cassini, the observatory's director,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:52.00,0:38:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,had been documenting their orbits in minute detail.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.00,0:39:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Jupiter's innermost moon Io
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.00,0:39:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is known to make a complete circuit around the gas giant
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.00,0:39:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,once every 1.77 Earth days `
Dialogue: 0,0:39:27.00,0:39:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that's every 42.5 hours.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.00,0:39:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, from Earth, we can see it disappear behind Jupiter
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.00,0:39:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and then re-emerge round the other side
Dialogue: 0,0:39:37.00,0:39:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,as it travels around in its orbit.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.00,0:39:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But here in Paris in the 1660s,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.00,0:39:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Giovanni Cassini had noticed
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.00,0:39:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that the timing of these eclipses seemed to vary,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.00,0:39:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,sometimes sooner, sometimes later than expected.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.00,0:40:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Soon after he arrived in Paris
Dialogue: 0,0:40:01.00,0:40:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Romer noticed that these fluctuations weren't happening at random.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.00,0:40:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,When the Earth was closer to Jupiter,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.00,0:40:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Io would be seen to disappear and re-emerge earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:15.00,0:40:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But as the year went by
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.00,0:40:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the Earth moved in its orbit around the sun
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.00,0:40:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,so that it was further away from Jupiter,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.00,0:40:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,then the eclipses appeared to happen later than expected.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.00,0:40:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Romer knew the moon always took the same time to travel around Jupiter.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.00,0:40:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,His great insight was to realise that the variations were due to the fact
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.00,0:40:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that light itself takes time to travel through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.00,0:40:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Here's how it works...
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.00,0:40:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The eclipses of Io appear later than expected
Dialogue: 0,0:40:54.00,0:40:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,when the Earth is further from Jupiter,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:57.00,0:41:01.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because light takes a longer time to cover the greater distance,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:01.00,0:41:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but they appear earlier when the Earth is closer
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.00,0:41:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because light needs less time to reach the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.00,0:41:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Light isn't instantaneous.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.00,0:41:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It travels at a finite speed.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.00,0:41:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Today, we've not only measured light's speed with incredible accuracy,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.00,0:41:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we've seen it in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.00,0:41:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is a video made by scientists at MIT,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.00,0:41:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,using a camera designed to monitor extremely fast, chemical reactions.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.00,0:41:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It has a shutter speed of around a picosecond.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.00,0:41:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,That's a millionth of a millionth of a second `
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.00,0:41:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the time it takes light to travel just a third of a millimetre.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.00,0:41:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, look what happens when I press play.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.00,0:42:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What you can see here is a pulse of laser light
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.00,0:42:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,moving through a water-filled bottle.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.00,0:42:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,To us, this would appear as the briefest of flashes,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.00,0:42:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but the camera reveals how the pulse travels through the bottle,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.00,0:42:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,scattering and bouncing around as it hits the water molecules.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.00,0:42:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Light travels so fast -
Dialogue: 0,0:42:38.00,0:42:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,300,000 kilometres per second
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.00,0:42:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that slowed down by the same amount,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.00,0:42:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a bullet would take an entire year
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.00,0:42:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to travel the length of the bottle.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:51.00,0:42:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's one thing to know that light travels at a finite speed,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:55.00,0:42:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,quite another to actually see it move.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:02.00,0:43:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The discovery of the speed of light was hugely significant.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.00,0:43:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Not least because it proved crucial
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.00,0:43:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to uncovering what light actually is.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:22.00,0:43:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Born in the summer of 1831,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.00,0:43:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,James Clerk Maxwell would become one of the leading lights
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.00,0:43:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,of 19th-century physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:31.00,0:43:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,GASPS APPLAUSE
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.00,0:43:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,His work on electricity and magnetism
Dialogue: 0,0:43:36.00,0:43:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was one of the greatest achievements of the age.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:43.00,0:43:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is Glenlair in south-west Scotland,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.00,0:43:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Maxwell's family home.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.00,0:43:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,While he was growing up here, he developed an insatiable curiosity about the world around him,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:54.00,0:43:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a desire to understand nature
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.00,0:43:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that he would never lose.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:11.00,0:44:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The young Maxwell seems to have taken great delight
Dialogue: 0,0:44:14.00,0:44:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in tormenting his parents and his nanny
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.00,0:44:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,by constantly asking them how things worked.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.00,0:44:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,"What's the go o'that?" he'd say.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:23.00,0:44:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,If anyone ventured an answer,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:25.00,0:44:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the young Maxwell would only be satisfied for a moment
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.00,0:44:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,before asking them how they knew.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:36.00,0:44:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Of course, none of this is particularly unusual for a child,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.00,0:44:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,but what sets Maxwell apart
Dialogue: 0,0:44:42.00,0:44:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is that he was just 14 years old
Dialogue: 0,0:44:44.00,0:44:47.00,English1,,0,0,0,,when he wrote his first scientific paper.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:47.00,0:44:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So young, that a friend of the family
Dialogue: 0,0:44:49.00,0:44:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,had to present it to the Royal Society of Edinburgh on his behalf.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.00,0:45:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Maxwell was one of the greatest scientists who ever lived
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.00,0:45:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and it was here that he carried out his most important work.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:12.00,0:45:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,During the 1860s,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:14.00,0:45:18.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Maxwell produced a virtuoso piece of mathematics
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.00,0:45:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that showed electricity and magnetism
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.00,0:45:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,were different aspects of the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.00,0:45:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But his calculations would show something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:29.00,0:45:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Quite by accident, they would reveal the true nature of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.00,0:45:37.00,English1,,0,0,0,,These are Maxwell's four famous equations
Dialogue: 0,0:45:37.00,0:45:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that describe the relationship between electric and magnetic fields.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:43.00,0:45:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Curl of E
Dialogue: 0,0:45:45.00,0:45:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is minus dB by dt.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:49.00,0:45:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,E is the electric field, B is the magnetic field.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:52.00,0:45:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Curl of B over mu nought...
Dialogue: 0,0:45:56.00,0:45:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,div of E equals zero...
Dialogue: 0,0:45:59.00,0:46:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,equals epsilon nought... ...  equals nought.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.00,0:46:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,With a bit of algebra and manipulation,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:04.00,0:46:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,these four equations can be combined to give one single equation.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:08.00,0:46:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So the way it's done is like this...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:11.00,0:46:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,We take the curl of curl of E...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.00,0:46:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Hidden deep within his mathematics
Dialogue: 0,0:46:16.00,0:46:21.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was something that even Maxwell didn't expect.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.00,0:46:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..epsilon nought... Grad E 2 div...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.00,0:46:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This second term is zero
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.00,0:46:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and I'm left with Del squared of E...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:30.00,0:46:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..minus mu nought, epsilon nought
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.00,0:46:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,D 2 E...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:36.00,0:46:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..by dt squared.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:41.00,0:46:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,This is the wave equation.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:44.00,0:46:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It tells us how an electromagnetic field
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.00,0:46:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,travels through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:48.00,0:46:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, the important bit is this here -
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.00,0:46:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,mu nought, epsilon nought -
Dialogue: 0,0:46:53.00,0:46:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because it's related to the speed that the wave is travelling.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.00,0:47:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In fact, the speed is given...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.00,0:47:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..by one over the square root of mu nought epsilon nought.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:06.00,0:47:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And if you work that out, you arrive at...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.00,0:47:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..3 times 10 to the power 8 metres per second,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.00,0:47:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,or 300,000 kilometres per second -
Dialogue: 0,0:47:16.00,0:47:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:20.00,0:47:24.00,English1,,0,0,0,,If electromagnetic waves moved at the speed of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:24.00,0:47:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it could only mean one thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:27.00,0:47:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Maxwell knew this had to be more than just a coincidence.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:32.00,0:47:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It meant that light itself had to be an electromagnetic wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.00,0:47:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The discovery that light is an electromagnetic wave
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.00,0:47:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,explains one of its most puzzling properties.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:58.00,0:48:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What Maxwell's equations show
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.00,0:48:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is that light consists of electric and magnetic waves travelling through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.00,0:48:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,So light is simply electric and magnetic vibrations
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.00,0:48:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,feeding off one another as they move.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:16.00,0:48:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And we now know that these electromagnetic waves have a remarkable property -
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.00,0:48:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,they don't need to be waves in anything,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:25.00,0:48:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,they can travel through empty space.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.00,0:48:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I remember first learning about this when I was in my second year at university.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:49.00,0:48:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I was in lecture hall 33AC21 of the physics department at the University of Surrey,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:55.00,0:48:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the lecturer was Dr Chivers,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.00,0:48:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and I remember turning to my friend next to me
Dialogue: 0,0:48:59.00,0:49:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and remarking on how incredible I thought this was.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.00,0:49:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,I could tell by his reaction that he thought I was a bit of a geek.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:07.00,0:49:12.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But, actually, it is incredible that in just a few lines of algebra,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:12.00,0:49:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,you can tell what light really is.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:19.00,0:49:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And the fact that light travels at a finite speed
Dialogue: 0,0:49:22.00,0:49:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,has enabled us to do something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:26.00,0:49:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It allows us to look into the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:32.00,0:49:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Looking at a mirror one metre away,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:34.00,0:49:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,you see yourself as you were six nanoseconds ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:38.00,0:49:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,From Earth, the moon appears as it was one second ago
Dialogue: 0,0:49:43.00,0:49:46.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the sun eight minutes in the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:46.00,0:49:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The further you look out in space, the further you look back in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:52.00,0:49:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Light from the cosmos's most distant objects
Dialogue: 0,0:49:56.00,0:50:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,has taken billions of years to reach the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:00.00,0:50:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But there's one source that has taken us so far back in time,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:04.00,0:50:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we've reached the very limit of what can be seen with light.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.00,0:50:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,In 1964, while converting a strange-looking horn antenna
Dialogue: 0,0:50:19.00,0:50:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,designed for early satellite communications
Dialogue: 0,0:50:22.00,0:50:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to make astronomical observations...
Dialogue: 0,0:50:27.00,0:50:30.00,English1,,0,0,0,,..Arno Penzias and Robert Wilson
Dialogue: 0,0:50:30.00,0:50:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,began to pick up a mysterious signal they couldn't explain.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.00,0:50:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Here, we had purposely picked a portion of the spectrum,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:48.00,0:50:49.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a wavelength of seven centimetres,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:49.00,0:50:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,where we expected nothing or almost nothing,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:53.00,0:50:55.00,English1,,0,0,0,,no radiation at all from the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.00,0:51:02.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Instead, what happened is that we found radiation
Dialogue: 0,0:51:02.00,0:51:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,coming into our antenna from all directions.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:05.00,0:51:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's just flooding in at us and, um,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:09.00,0:51:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,clearly was orders of magnitude more than we expected from the galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.00,0:51:22.00,English1,,0,0,0,,At first, they dismissed it as noise,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:22.00,0:51:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,something unwanted, generated by the antenna itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.00,0:51:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Now, we had some suspicion
Dialogue: 0,0:51:29.00,0:51:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,because the throat of the antenna came into the cab and was a little bit warmer,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.00,0:51:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and that was an attractive place for pigeons,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:36.00,0:51:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,at least a pair of pigeons who liked to stay there, especially in the cold winter.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:41.00,0:51:44.00,English1,,0,0,0,,We didn't mind that because they flew away when we came,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.00,0:51:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,except that they had coated the surface with a white sticky material
Dialogue: 0,0:51:48.00,0:51:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which might not only absorb radio waves but emit radio waves,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.00,0:51:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,which could be part or maybe all of our result.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:02.00,0:52:05.00,English1,,0,0,0,,With the antenna cleaned, and the pigeons -
Dialogue: 0,0:52:05.00,0:52:07.00,English1,,0,0,0,,well, it didn't end well for the pigeons -
Dialogue: 0,0:52:07.00,0:52:11.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Penzias and Wilson began searching for an astronomical explanation.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.00,0:52:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But the signal wasn't coming from anything in our own galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.00,0:52:19.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Nor did it appear to be coming from any other galaxy either.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:19.00,0:52:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It seemed to be coming from everywhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:25.00,0:52:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,No matter when we looked, day or night, winter or summer,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:28.00,0:52:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,this background of radiation appeared everywhere in the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:34.00,0:52:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was not tied to our galaxy or any other known source of radio waves.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:39.00,0:52:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It was rather as if the whole Universe had been warmed up
Dialogue: 0,0:52:42.00,0:52:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to a temperature about three degrees above absolute zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:50.00,0:52:54.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And so we were left with the astonishing result
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.00,0:52:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that this radiation was coming from somewhere
Dialogue: 0,0:52:57.00,0:53:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,in really deep cosmic space...
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.00,0:53:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,...beyond any radio sources
Dialogue: 0,0:53:04.00,0:53:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that any of us knew about or even dreamed existed.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.00,0:53:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What they'd discovered was light so ancient,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:25.00,0:53:28.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it had been stretched out into microwaves
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.00,0:53:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and cooled to just a few scant degrees above absolute zero,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.00,0:53:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,light that had been travelling to Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:53:35.00,0:53:38.00,English1,,0,0,0,,for almost the entire age of the Universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:38.00,0:53:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It hadn't come from a distant galaxy
Dialogue: 0,0:53:40.00,0:53:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and it was far older than any star.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:43.00,0:53:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Penzias and Wilson had discovered that the entire Universe was awash with light
Dialogue: 0,0:53:48.00,0:53:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,from the embers of the Big Bang itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.00,0:54:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Called the Cosmic Microwave Background,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.00,0:54:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it was released when the Universe was just 370,000 years old
Dialogue: 0,0:54:15.00,0:54:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and it gives us a snapshot of the cosmos in its infancy.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:24.00,0:54:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,And here it is,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.00,0:54:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the latest image of the Cosmic Microwave Background,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:29.00,0:54:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,taken by the Planck satellite and published in early 2013.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:33.00,0:54:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The different colours are fluctuations in temperature in the early Universe
Dialogue: 0,0:54:39.00,0:54:41.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the information they contain
Dialogue: 0,0:54:41.00,0:54:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,has proved priceless to cosmologists.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:46.00,0:54:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The tiny variations in temperature are caused by matter clumping together
Dialogue: 0,0:54:51.00,0:54:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,into what will eventually become stars and galaxies.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:57.00,0:55:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But what's truly remarkable about this image
Dialogue: 0,0:55:00.00,0:55:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is that it's not just light from the early Universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:03.00,0:55:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's the very first light there ever was.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:31.00,0:55:34.00,English1,,0,0,0,,During the first era of its life,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.00,0:55:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the Universe was a fireball of hot dense plasma
Dialogue: 0,0:55:39.00,0:55:43.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that trapped light, preventing it from moving.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:45.00,0:55:50.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Then, as the cosmos cooled, the plasma condensed,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:50.00,0:55:53.00,English1,,0,0,0,,forming the first atoms...
Dialogue: 0,0:55:58.00,0:56:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,...and the first light,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:00.00,0:56:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,light that would become the Cosmic Microwave Background
Dialogue: 0,0:56:04.00,0:56:08.00,English1,,0,0,0,,was released into the Universe
Dialogue: 0,0:56:22.00,0:56:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,It's sort of hard to express what an astonishing achievement this is,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:27.00,0:56:31.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that from our small planet, orbiting an unremarkable star,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.00,0:56:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we've reached out into the Universe
Dialogue: 0,0:56:35.00,0:56:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and seen as far as it's possible to see with light.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:55.00,0:56:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The discovery of the Cosmic Microwave Background
Dialogue: 0,0:56:58.00,0:57:03.00,English1,,0,0,0,,appeared to complete our picture of the Universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:03.00,0:57:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the final chapter in our use of light
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.00,0:57:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to explore the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.00,0:57:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Understanding the nature of light has allowed us to illuminate our world.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:16.00,0:57:20.00,English1,,0,0,0,,We've captured it from the depths of space and the beginning of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.00,0:57:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,At the smallest scales, light has uncovered
Dialogue: 0,0:57:23.00,0:57:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,the microscopic structure of living things,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.00,0:57:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and at the largest,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:27.00,0:57:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's shown us our place in the cosmos
Dialogue: 0,0:57:29.00,0:57:32.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and told us the story of the stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:32.00,0:57:35.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Virtually everything we know about the Universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:35.00,0:57:39.00,English1,,0,0,0,,we know because it's been revealed by light.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:46.00,0:57:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,But just as it seemed light would lead us
Dialogue: 0,0:57:48.00,0:57:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to a complete understanding of everything...
Dialogue: 0,0:57:54.00,0:57:56.00,English1,,0,0,0,,...in the last 30 years,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:56.00,0:57:59.00,English1,,0,0,0,,it's shown us something disturbing.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:00.00,0:58:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The vast majority of the cosmos can't be seen at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:11.00,0:58:14.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Far from being a Universe of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:14.00,0:58:17.00,English1,,0,0,0,,much of it is hidden in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:22.00,0:58:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Next time,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.00,0:58:26.00,English1,,0,0,0,,how scientists came to the realisation
Dialogue: 0,0:58:26.00,0:58:29.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that more than 99 percent of the Universe
Dialogue: 0,0:58:29.00,0:58:33.00,English1,,0,0,0,,lies concealed in the shadows,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:33.00,0:58:36.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the extraordinary quest
Dialogue: 0,0:58:36.00,0:58:40.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to uncover what's out there in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:43.00,0:58:45.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Whether you want to step into the light
Dialogue: 0,0:58:45.00,0:58:48.00,English1,,0,0,0,,or explore the mysteries of the dark,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:48.00,0:58:52.00,English1,,0,0,0,,let the Open University inspire you. Go to...
Dialogue: 0,0:58:55.00,0:58:58.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and follow links to The Open University.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:58.00,0:59:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Subtitles by Red Bee Media Ltd
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.00,0:00:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在黑暗的笼罩下
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.00,0:00:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,世界从视野中消失
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.00,0:00:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没有光，我根本无法知道我身边的环境有些啥
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.00,0:00:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我被包裹起来了，被四周未知的事物
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.00,0:00:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,笼罩起来了
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.00,0:00:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人类历史上的大部分时间
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.00,0:00:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当太阳落下黑夜降临
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.00,0:00:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们面对黑暗无能为力
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.00,0:00:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但几个世纪以来
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.00,0:00:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们已经发展出我们自己的照明光源
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.00,0:01:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们点亮我们的房子，街道，城市
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.00,0:01:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就这样，我们驱逐了黑暗
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.00,0:01:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在用光来照亮我们的世界的同时
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.00,0:01:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们也发现了更多有关光的性质
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.00,0:01:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光也向我们展现了宇宙的更多秘密
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.00,0:01:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们曾望向星空深处...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.00,0:01:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...回到时间开始的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.00,0:01:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但当我们向更深处望去
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.00,0:02:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们便认识到我们看到的是多么小
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.00,0:02:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也意识到，宇宙的最大谜团
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.00,0:02:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,依然隐藏于黑暗之中
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.00,0:02:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,本质上来说，光明与黑暗就是
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.00,0:02:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,关于我们宇宙的故事
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.10,0:02:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,包括我们所了解的和不了解的所有事情
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.00,0:02:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这一切都始于光
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.00,0:02:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光是我们认识世界的一种必不可少的方法
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.00,0:02:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也很容易被看着是理所当然的
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.00,0:03:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但几个世纪以来，理解光到底是什么
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.00,0:03:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,曾经是长时间没解决的科学问题之一
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.00,0:03:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在理解光的性质的道路上
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.00,0:03:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最初的几步是在公元前三世纪
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.00,0:03:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由著名的希腊数学家欧几里德迈出的
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.00,0:03:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他从思考一件最明显的事情开始着手
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.00,0:03:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们大部分人都不会去想这件事
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.00,0:03:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将一把很小的椅子近距离的放在摄像机前
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.00,0:03:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就会在屏幕上产生一个很大的图像
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.00,0:03:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但因为在日常生活中我们并不常见很小的椅子
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.00,0:03:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的大脑便误以为
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.00,0:03:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它是一把放在房间中普通尺寸的椅子
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.00,0:03:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,造成这种错觉发生的原因
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.00,0:04:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是因为，在判断距离上
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.00,0:04:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的大脑依赖一个简单的基本事实-
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.00,0:04:06.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,物体离我们的视线越远
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.20,0:04:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它在我们的眼睛里就显得更小
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.00,0:04:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,通过关注究竟为什么
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.00,0:04:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,远处的物体可以和摆的很近的小尺寸的物体
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.00,0:04:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,显示出相同的尺寸
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.00,0:04:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...这使得欧几里德发现了光的最基本的性质之一
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.00,0:04:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很明显，伦敦眼比我的手指要大得多，这我知道
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.00,0:04:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但对我来说它们看起来一样大
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.00,0:04:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么，我们该如何解释这一现象呢？
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.00,0:04:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,嗯，欧几里德提出了一个很简单的解决方法
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.00,0:05:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从我的手指一直到摩天轮的顶端
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.00,0:05:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我的眼睛，我的手指和摩天轮的顶端
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.00,0:05:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一定都是位于同一条线上
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.00,0:05:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是欧几里德的洞察力并不仅限于解释这透视的技巧
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.00,0:05:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它揭示了关于光自身的一个基本事实
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.00,0:05:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,欧几里德发现光是沿着直线传播的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.00,0:05:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,意识到它是如何传播的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.00,0:05:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,标志着我们开始科学地理解光是什么
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.00,0:05:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这也意味着如果我们可以转变光的直线路径
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.00,0:05:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们就可以改变我们看世界的方式
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.00,0:06:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这一跨越在之后的2000年都没有实现
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.00,0:06:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最终实现这一跨越的是，在意大利的文艺复兴时期
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.00,0:06:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由现代科学的奠基人之一实现的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.00,0:06:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1609年的夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.00,0:06:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略·伽利莱完成了一个短途却改变命运的旅行
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.00,0:06:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从故乡帕多瓦省到威尼斯
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.00,0:06:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是威尼斯共和国的首都
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.00,0:06:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略有着火红的头发，大胡子
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.00,0:06:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人们知道他很喜欢葡萄酒，慷慨好客
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.00,0:06:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也知道他反正统的观点
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.00,0:06:53.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在那个时候，作为一个自然哲学家和数学家
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.50,0:06:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他的声望也很高
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.00,0:07:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人们认为他是威尼斯共和国的宝贵财富
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.00,0:07:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,虽然，作为一个教授，他有固定的收入
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.00,0:07:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略却总是摆脱不了财务上的麻烦
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.00,0:07:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当他的父亲在1591年去世时
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.00,0:07:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略，作为家中幸存的兄弟姐妹里最年长的一个
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.00,0:07:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,成为了家里的顶梁柱
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.00,0:07:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并实际上承担了供养自己弟弟的责任
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.00,0:07:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他弟弟是一个贫穷的流浪音乐家
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.00,0:07:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也承担了他妹妹们的嫁妆费
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.00,0:07:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当他来到威尼斯的时候
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.00,0:07:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他仍旧欠自己两个妹夫一大笔钱
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.00,0:07:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以他一直在寻找一个能赚钱的项目
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.00,0:07:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那年夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.00,0:07:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,威尼斯到处都在传说一种装置
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.00,0:07:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它可以做那些看似不可能的事情...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.00,0:07:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..那就是一种荷兰的间谍玻璃
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.00,0:07:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以拉近远处的物体
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.00,0:08:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这正是伽利略所寻找的机遇
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.00,0:08:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,回到17世纪
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.00,0:08:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,被称为间谍玻璃的小望远镜还属于尖端技术
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.00,0:08:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而内部的运作细节则是被严守的秘密
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.00,0:08:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略也只是知道它是由两个透镜放在镜筒里组成
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.00,0:08:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以他在开发自己的望远镜时，他也把制作方法作为高度机密
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.00,0:08:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但我们从一份购物单上知道了
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.00,0:08:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他在环礁湖外的慕拉诺的小岛上购置了镜片
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.00,0:08:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,又因为手头没有现存的工具，他不得不临时拼凑
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.00,0:08:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,举个例子，买一个炮兵球
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.00,0:08:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,去打磨透镜表面的曲面
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.00,0:08:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,众所周知第一副眼镜的生产
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.00,0:08:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是在13世纪的中期
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.00,0:09:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那时的人们发现了玻璃能弯曲光线的奇怪的性质
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.00,0:09:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但与眼镜不同的是
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.00,0:09:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,小型望远镜，早期的望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.00,0:09:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,需要通过一个非常特殊的安放
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.00,0:09:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来将镜头组合
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.00,0:09:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是伽利略的望远镜工作原理
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.00,0:09:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光线从远处的物体上投射过来
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.00,0:09:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以当它们到达第一片透镜时几乎是平行的
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.00,0:09:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是物镜，而且是平凸型的
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.00,0:09:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是说这个镜片一边是平面另一边是曲面
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.00,0:09:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这类的镜片过去常用于治疗远视眼
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.00,0:09:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的作用就是使光线弯折彼此聚拢
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.00,0:09:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样就能让这些光汇聚在一点
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.00,0:09:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但在这个焦点之前
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.00,0:09:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略放置了他的第二个镜片，目镜，一个平凹镜
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.00,0:09:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就使得被弯曲的光线再次还原
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.00,0:09:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样一来光线就能平行射出，进入我们的眼中
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.00,0:10:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然后眼睛的晶状体将光线聚焦到视网膜上
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.00,0:10:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么望远镜的放大倍数取决于
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.00,0:10:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,两个镜片的焦距比
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.00,0:10:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是距离F1和F2
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.00,0:10:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略的困难
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.00,0:10:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是在磨薄他的物镜上
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.00,0:10:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将物镜尽可能地磨薄
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.00,0:10:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为的是使F1的长度最大化
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.00,0:10:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为如果它可以做到这一点
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.00,0:10:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他的望远镜就可以有更大的放大率
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.00,0:10:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,仅用了几周的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.00,0:10:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略的望远镜就达到了8倍的放大倍率
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.00,0:10:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且威力远比那些原来的小望远镜要强大得多
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.00,0:10:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他现在唯一要做的
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.00,0:10:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是靠他的新发明赚钱
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.00,0:10:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,作为一个爱出风头的人，在1609年8月21日
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.00,0:10:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略爬上了城市的钟塔
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.00,0:10:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【钟声】
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.00,0:11:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【电梯里的音乐】“来自伊帕内玛的女孩”
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.00,0:11:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然啦，他当年走的是楼梯！
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.00,0:11:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在塔顶，在一大群威尼斯贵族和参议员的面前
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.00,0:11:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略向他们展示了他的望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.00,0:11:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,结果是轰动性的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.00,0:11:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用这个望远镜，威尼斯人可以看见正在靠近的船只
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.00,0:11:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,比肉眼看到的早2个小时
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.00,0:11:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,能够提前知道谁正在驶向岸边，其军事和经济上的优势这一点
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.00,0:11:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,引起了当天在场的所有人的注意
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.00,0:11:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,3天之后，作为一个一鸣惊人的人物
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.00,0:12:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略将自己的望远镜作为礼物敬献给了公爵
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.00,0:12:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,作为回报，他有了一个双薪的工作
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.00,0:12:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来养家糊口
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.00,0:12:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现今他的经济有了保障
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.00,0:12:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略便继续开发威力更大的望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.00,0:12:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并通过望远镜，这一可弯曲光线的能力
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.00,0:12:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来改变我们对宇宙的看法
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.00,0:12:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是1610年伽利略出版的一本书
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.00,0:12:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,书名叫“Sidereus Nuncius”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.00,0:12:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这拉丁文译过来就是“星际信使”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.00,0:12:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,书中，他记录了自己第一次观察夜晚的星空
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.00,0:12:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是第一次有人
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.00,0:12:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使用肉眼以外的东西来观察星空
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.00,0:12:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,今天看来，很难想像
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.00,0:13:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这本书中所包含的内容怎么会有争议性
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.00,0:13:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但你要记得在写这本书的年代
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.00,0:13:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人们认为天空的属性只有上帝才能知道
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.00,0:13:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而地球则被认为是在宇宙的中心
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.00,0:13:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些是他画的月亮
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.00,0:13:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,自古以来，人们认为所有天堂上的东西都是完美的球体
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.00,0:13:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是伽利略用他的望远镜，看见了月球表面的纹理
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.00,0:13:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,深坑和高山
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.00,0:13:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从投影在月球表面的阴影推算
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.00,0:13:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他估计它们大约有6千米高
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.00,0:13:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也证明了天堂是不完美的
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.00,0:13:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他的望远镜开始揭开天堂的真相
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.00,0:14:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,望远镜所看到的星星数目
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.00,0:14:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,十倍于肉眼所看到
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.00,0:14:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在书的最后几章中
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.00,0:14:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略报告了他发现的四颗星星
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.00,0:14:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几乎连成一条直线
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.00,0:14:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,紧挨着木星
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.00,0:14:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他的图画显示出它们位置每晚的变化
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.00,0:14:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,虽然它们在移动，但是移动时总是沿着同一条直线
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.00,0:14:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由此，伽利略推断它们的轨道是绕着木星的
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.00,0:14:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们并不是星星，它们相当于木星的月亮
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.00,0:14:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,通过他的望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.00,0:14:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略找到了证据
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.00,0:14:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,推翻了广为接受的教条
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.00,0:14:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是，地球就是核心
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.00,0:14:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙万物都围绕着它运行
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.00,0:14:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,想一想运行于木星的轨道上的那些卫星
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.00,0:14:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这意味着并不是所有的东西都绕着地球运行
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.00,0:15:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就更不用说作为宇宙的中心了
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.00,0:15:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球只是另一颗行星
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.00,0:15:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,望远镜使得伽利略能够
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.00,0:15:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,瞥见宇宙的真实属性
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.00,0:15:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以及我们在其中的位置
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.00,0:15:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是这种操纵光的方法
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.00,0:15:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有着另一个强大的应用
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.00,0:15:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那便是让我们能看到另一个世界
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.00,0:15:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【钟声】
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.00,0:15:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在17世纪的伦敦
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.00,0:15:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这个世纪最杰出的科学家之一
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.00,0:16:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,正在用另一种方式使用透镜
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.00,0:16:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,罗伯特·胡克在了解了望远镜的基本原理后
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.00,0:16:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,便将它运用在制造显微镜上
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.00,0:16:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,伽利略用望远镜发现了天空的新世界
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.00,0:16:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而胡克则用显微镜发现了一个
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.00,0:16:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,非常非常小的新世界
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.00,0:16:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这二者有一个不同之处，因为伽利略所展现的
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.00,0:16:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是世界更为辽阔更为丰富的一面
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.00,0:16:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但那至少还是个能让人依稀感受得到的世界
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.00,0:16:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为你可以仰望天空看到群星
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.00,0:16:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然而胡克所展现的
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.00,0:16:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,则是一种全新的壮观的世界
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.00,0:16:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是在物质的最小粒子里
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.00,0:17:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个人们之前从未想过的世界
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.00,0:17:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人们甚至没有意识到
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.00,0:17:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是由显微镜所展现出的世界
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.00,0:17:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,胡克用他的显微镜
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.00,0:17:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,观察了大量的物质和活的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.00,0:17:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但正是他所画下的他所看到的昆虫身体的精致细节
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.00,0:17:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使得这些画变得非常有名
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.00,0:17:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里，你可以看到一个跳蚤，人蚤，是一种极小的生物
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.00,0:17:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这里我们有一个从“显微图谱”里弄过来的印图
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.00,0:17:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是胡克所创造的巨大跳蚤的形状
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.00,0:17:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且这也着实有许多壮观的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.00,0:17:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这图当时折叠在书中的，所以它真的是非常大
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.00,0:17:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有些人说它跟猫差不多大
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.00,0:17:53.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是一个艺术品，真的，我的意思是说
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.50,0:17:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这幅画里有这么多错综复杂的细节
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.00,0:17:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,确实，而且在胡克之前并没有像这样的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.00,0:18:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们真的是史无前例的
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.00,0:18:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且阴影和图像的质量也是超一流的
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.00,0:18:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并且也很精准，我的意思是说，是的，它确实很精准
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.00,0:18:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我昨天刚好看了，跳蚤的照片，那真是
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.00,0:18:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用电子显微镜所照的
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.00,0:18:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而两者真的没有什么区别，胡克和
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.00,0:18:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,电镜的图像
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.00,0:18:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是一幅苍蝇复眼的图片
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.00,0:18:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是胡克第一次展示如此惊人的细节
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.00,0:18:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是一幅苍蝇的脚的图片
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.00,0:18:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,胡克向人们展示了这个脚有很小的刺凸在上面
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.00,0:18:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就使得它可以扣紧物体表面的空隙
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.00,0:18:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这张图片看起来没有之前的有趣，也没有之前的复杂
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.00,0:18:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它看起来并不非常有趣
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.00,0:18:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是，事实上，它真的是一幅意义深远的图片
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.00,0:18:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为这是胡克观察的一个很薄的软木塞的切片
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.00,0:18:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他用小刀切下来的
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.00,0:19:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并观察组成它的每一小部分
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.00,0:19:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他把他们称之为气孔，之后又把它们称之为洞穴
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.00,0:19:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,再后来叫它们盒子，最后他称它们为细胞
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.00,0:19:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,细胞，是的，那个被广泛接受了的术语
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.00,0:19:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这只是其中的一小部分，不只是软木塞，还包括所有的生物
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.00,0:19:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以这是一个极其重要的发现
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.00,0:19:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这一称呼也成为了生物学的标准
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.00,0:19:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使用玻璃弯曲光线
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.00,0:19:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,揭示了我们在宇宙中的真正位置...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.00,0:20:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..和拥有复杂结构的微观世界
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.00,0:20:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们看到的越多
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.00,0:20:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我知道的就越多
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.00,0:20:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,随着每一次深入了解新的光的本质
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.00,0:20:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对宇宙的了解也会更进一步
Dialogue: 0,0:20:34.00,0:20:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,下一个发现
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.00,0:20:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将把我们带入更深的一层...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.00,0:20:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..使我们能够理解星星的故事
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.00,0:21:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这一切都起源于胡克通过他的显微镜所瞥见的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.00,0:21:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是罗伯特·胡克著的《显微图谱》
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.00,0:21:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,出版于1664年
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.00,0:21:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,距今350年
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.00,0:21:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,书里充满了...
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.00,0:21:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..他的著名的图形
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.00,0:21:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这张是他的跳蚤图
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.00,0:21:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看到它的原始形态真是令人难以置信
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.00,0:21:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的尺寸真的和猫有一拼！
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.00,0:21:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些图片真的抓住了公众的想象力也使得这本书变的非常有亲合力
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.00,0:21:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但对我而言，《显微图谱》带给我的不仅仅是这些
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.00,0:21:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,作为一个物理学家最吸引我的一章
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.00,0:21:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是几乎不含图的一章
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.00,0:21:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是这里的这一章-
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.00,0:21:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,“从白云母和其他薄片样本"
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.00,0:21:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,"可以观察到的颜色"
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.00,0:21:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里胡克描述了彩虹五彩斑斓的图案
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.00,0:21:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他通过他的显微镜发现
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.00,0:22:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当光穿过很薄的材料时
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.00,0:22:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,比如肥皂泡和白云母片
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.00,0:22:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一种有许多薄层的硅酸盐矿物组成的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.00,0:22:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那时，白光被认为是像太阳光一样的，是纯净的光，
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.00,0:22:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它直接来自上帝
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.00,0:22:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,于是胡克得出结论---他看到的颜色
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.00,0:22:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一定是以某种方式被添加到光里去了
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.00,0:22:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当光通过材料时
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.00,0:22:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那些颜色的的确确地出现了
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.00,0:22:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是胡克的关于色光理论
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.00,0:22:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,正要被他最有力的竞争对手所挑战
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.00,0:22:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,艾萨克·牛顿是世界上最受人尊敬的科学家之一...
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.00,0:22:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..最为人所熟知的是他的万有引力理论
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.00,0:23:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,正如他的引力定律一样
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.00,0:23:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,发现光的本质
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.00,0:23:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也是牛顿最著名的成就
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.00,0:23:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但至于牛顿是如何开始这项工作的，就鲜为人知了
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.00,0:23:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且这一次 ，再没什么水果砸在他的头上
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.00,0:23:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里是剑河下游的南岸
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.00,0:23:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一片沉寂在剑河堤岸的草场
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.00,0:23:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但1664年牛顿拜访这里时，情况则是大不一样
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.00,0:23:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,700多年来,每年9月这个地方将会
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.00,0:23:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,变成它的，最鼎盛时期的原貌----欧洲最大的展览会
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.00,0:23:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每年的这几个星期，人们都会涌向这片地方
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.00,0:23:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为了这个一年一度的商业和狂欢的节日
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.00,0:23:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【狗叫声】
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.00,0:24:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【剑的碰撞声和掌声】
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.00,0:24:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这整片地方都挤满了临时的摊位
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.00,0:24:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,农产品，白兰地酒坊，珠宝商金匠，丝绸商人
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.00,0:24:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里也有长蛇缓舞，木偶剧表演，音乐表演
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.00,0:24:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,各种各样的诱惑
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.00,0:24:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,挤在这一排排木亭和帐篷里
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.00,0:24:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,剑河下游的展览会是一个你可以买到你所想的任何东西的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.00,0:24:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但当牛顿来到这里时，据说他只买了一样东西-
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.00,0:24:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个棱镜
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.00,0:24:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他买下了它是因为它展示了
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.00,0:24:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,胡克当年从显微镜看到的相同的戏法
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.00,0:25:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,牛顿后来写道，用他新买的小玩意
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.00,0:25:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他想要“试一下这种有名的色彩现象”...
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.00,0:25:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..这是一个相当低调的引言
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.00,0:25:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这一工作会导致对光的本性的一种深刻认识
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.00,0:25:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,牛顿设计了一个独创性的实验
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.00,0:25:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来精确地观察这些彩虹的颜色到底是怎么产生的
Dialogue: 0,0:25:36.00,0:25:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从而检验胡克的理论，这个理论认为
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.00,0:25:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那些颜色是由棱镜本身产生的
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.00,0:25:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是牛顿自己画的实验图，他称之为“判决性实验”
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.00,0:25:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在这里，他放置了一个棱镜
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.00,0:26:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他在他自己床边的百叶窗上开了个洞，让阳光照射进来
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.00,0:26:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,阳光穿过棱镜，把色光投影在一个光屏上
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.00,0:26:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,好，这是我的光源
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.00,0:26:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是我的棱镜
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.00,0:26:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果我仔细地调整棱镜
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.00,0:26:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我就可以把光投影到在后面的立柱上
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.00,0:26:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，这没有什么新东西
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.00,0:26:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,人们知道棱镜可以产生色光
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.00,0:26:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但牛顿接下来要做的事情，之前就没有人做过
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.00,0:26:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他先用一道缝隙孤立出一种颜色的光
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.00,0:26:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以这种情况下
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.00,0:26:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,只有橙色的光
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.00,0:26:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,接着他又让橙色的光穿过第二个棱镜
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.00,0:26:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这时，如果胡克是对的
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.00,0:26:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么这个棱镜就会在这个橙色上再加上别的颜色
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.00,0:26:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,重新还原成彩虹
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.00,0:27:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但牛顿所看到的还是橙色
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.00,0:27:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,棱镜并没有添加额外的颜色
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.00,0:27:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,于是他断定这个光的颜色一定是包含最开始的白光中
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.00,0:27:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那束白光是不纯的
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.00,0:27:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而棱镜并没有给那束光添加什么
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.00,0:27:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相反，棱镜把光分成了原来组成它的部分
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.00,0:27:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,牛顿将这些组成白光的颜色命名为
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.00,0:27:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,“光谱”
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.00,0:27:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而当这一发现和望远镜结合在一起的时候
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.00,0:27:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它将向我们展示难以置信的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.00,0:27:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光谱将向我们准确揭示
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.00,0:27:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们所仰望的星空的真实模样
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.00,0:27:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是一个分光仪
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.00,0:27:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当太阳光照进来时，它就被分解为组成它的色光
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.00,0:27:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且比你用简单的棱镜分散的更细致
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.00,0:27:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在，通过这个摄像机
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.00,0:27:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我就能向你展示我所看到的
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.00,0:28:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我要检查它是否正常工作
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.00,0:28:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,好的，可以
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.00,0:28:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当科学家在19世纪中期第一次进行这种尝试...
Dialogue: 0,0:28:11.00,0:28:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我把这个分光仪放在上面
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.00,0:28:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..他们看到了一个完全出乎意料的结果
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.00,0:28:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以看到彩色光谱，和牛顿当年看到的一样
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.00,0:28:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但如果你更靠近点看，你还能看到点别的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.00,0:28:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它不是连续的
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.00,0:28:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它被许多黑线所打断
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.00,0:28:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些光谱中有缝隙
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.00,0:28:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不久人们就意识到
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.00,0:28:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些空隙是由于太阳的外层大气原子
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.00,0:28:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,吸收来自太阳内部特定的波长的光形成的
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.00,0:28:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样一来，人们就可以用它们
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.00,0:28:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来弄清楚组成太阳的化学成分了
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.00,0:29:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每一种元素只吸收特定模式的波长-
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.00,0:29:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一份光学指纹
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.00,0:29:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以用来确定你在星空中看见的
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.00,0:29:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,任何发光物体的化学物质成分
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.00,0:29:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在罗马
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.00,0:29:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有一个人通过这个技术来研究
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.00,0:29:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那些来自其它星星上的光
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.00,0:29:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,安吉洛·西奇神父是一个不同寻常的牧师
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.00,0:29:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他魅力超凡却被他的耶稣会士视为异端
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.00,0:29:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那是因为他同时也是一个物理教授
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.00,0:29:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对天文学具有福音派的热情
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.00,0:29:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在1852年
Dialogue: 0,0:29:54.00,0:29:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,西奇被任命为梵蒂冈天文台主任
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.00,0:30:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在一年之内，他在圣伊格纳斯教堂的屋顶
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.00,0:30:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,建了一座新天文台，就在城市的心脏地区
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.00,0:30:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在那时，许多的天文学家都热衷于绘制星星的位置
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.00,0:30:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并且在描绘它们在天空中的运动轨迹
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.00,0:30:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但西奇与众不同
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.00,0:30:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他想知道它们究竟是什么
Dialogue: 0,0:30:23.00,0:30:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就这样，在这个制高点，高于罗马城街道的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.00,0:30:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他开始一丝不苟地分析它们发出来的光
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.00,0:30:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天文台的望远镜上加装了一个分光仪
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.00,0:30:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,西奇神父辛苦地记录了
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.00,0:30:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,超过4000颗星星的光谱
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.00,0:31:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是西奇著的书“Le Stelle”，星星
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.00,0:31:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他在1877年出版了这本书
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.00,0:31:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,翻看这本书时
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.00,0:31:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以看见他做的许多观测
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.00,0:31:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这一篇格外有意思
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.00,0:31:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它显示了他记录的光谱
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.00,0:31:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,上面的一条是来自太阳的
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.00,0:31:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这第二条则是星星的光谱
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.00,0:31:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来自天狼星A，大犬座主星
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.00,0:31:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是夜空中最亮的一颗恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.00,0:31:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,距离地球8.6光年
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.00,0:31:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,发出的光是太阳的20倍之多
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.00,0:31:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以从它的光谱中看到这些排列清楚的条带
Dialogue: 0,0:31:48.00,0:31:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是氢元素的特有标志
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.00,0:31:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为它相对来说还是一颗年轻的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.00,0:32:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙中那些最热的，最亮的星
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.00,0:32:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光谱中都富含有两种明亮的元素
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.00,0:32:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,氢元素和氦元素
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.00,0:32:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但随着年龄的增长，它们会变冷
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.00,0:32:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们的光谱也显示，出现了许多较重的元素
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.00,0:32:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这第三条是来自恒星参宿四的
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.00,0:32:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它是一颗红巨星
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.00,0:32:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的生命已经快走到了的尽头
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.00,0:32:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因此你可以看到这有许多条带
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.00,0:32:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那是由许多不同的元素组成的
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.00,0:32:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些图片是多么的引人注目
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.00,0:32:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我的意思是说，这真是天文学史上的最关键的时刻之一
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.00,0:32:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以只通过检测远处的星所射来的光
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.00,0:32:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就可以知道它的组成
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.00,0:33:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但正因为西奇把这么多不同年龄的星分门别类
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.00,0:33:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他的观测导致了更深刻的事情-
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.00,0:33:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,通过分析星光
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.00,0:33:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以确定恒星的生命周期...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:27.00,0:33:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..它们何时出生...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.00,0:33:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..它们何时又将衰亡
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.00,0:33:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,理解光谱
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.00,0:33:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,让我们可以读到恒星的故事
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.00,0:33:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,想起来都让人难以置信
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.00,0:33:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,始于黑屋子里的一个简单实验
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.00,0:34:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以揭示出如此之多有关宇宙的事情
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.00,0:34:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那些来自夜晚天空中极小亮点的微光
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.00,0:34:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,其中居然包含了太空的史诗剧
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.00,0:34:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但光谱能够告诉我们的不光只这些
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.00,0:34:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如今，我们知道光谱是由不同波长的光组成的
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.00,0:34:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并且那些波长远远超出了我们人眼的可见范围
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.00,0:34:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光谱中，从无线电通讯中使用的最长的波长
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.00,0:34:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,到最短的波长，伽马射线
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.00,0:34:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,涵盖了30个数量级的范围
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.00,0:34:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最长波长比最短波长要
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.00,0:34:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大1后面跟30个0倍
Dialogue: 0,0:34:54.00,0:34:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这个数量级跨度用重量来衡量
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.00,0:35:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就好比从一粒沙子
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.00,0:35:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,到地球上所有海水的重量的跨度
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.00,0:35:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在这个巨大的数量级范围中
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.00,0:35:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可见光-我们可以看见的频率-
Dialogue: 0,0:35:09.00,0:35:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最大波长只是最小波长的两倍
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.00,0:35:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,把这个拿到重量上来做比较
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.00,0:35:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像这个卵石和它的大小的两倍
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.00,0:35:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们一切就绪了吗，博士？嗯，我想是的
Dialogue: 0,0:35:28.00,0:35:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在整个20世纪里
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.00,0:35:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,面对全光谱，打开我们的眼界
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.00,0:35:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,揭示了更多有关宇宙的事情
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.00,0:35:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果你有一双红外眼，这便是你所看到的天空的样子
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.00,0:35:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,红外线让我们可以看见宇宙中最冷的星星
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.00,0:35:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而射电望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.00,0:35:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对长的波长十分灵敏
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.00,0:35:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,揭示了骚动的宇宙...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.00,0:35:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是射电望远镜所捕获到的激烈事件
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:36:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爆炸的恒星和星系
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.00,0:36:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..人造卫星则翱翔在天际
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.00,0:36:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,捕捉短波长的紫外线
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.00,0:36:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,轨道天文台(OAO)从热的恒星捕捉到了紫外光
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.00,0:36:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为大气层的阻挡，地面望远镜对此无能为力
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.00,0:36:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这里是最新的窗口 - 伽马射线 -
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.00,0:36:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,非常像是高能的X射线
Dialogue: 0,0:36:23.00,0:36:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,能看见可见光之外的光
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.00,0:36:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,让我们能深入到宇宙的深处
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.00,0:36:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我对这一成果十分骄傲
Dialogue: 0,0:36:31.00,0:36:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我也是，当我猛然听到这个发现时
Dialogue: 0,0:36:42.00,0:36:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这一事实证明了光是一种
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.00,0:36:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,探索宇宙非常有用的工具
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.00,0:36:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这取决于它自身最神秘的性质之一
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.00,0:36:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光的行为像波一样
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.00,0:36:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但如果它像波一样的话，那么这个波在什么里面？
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.00,0:37:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,波通过水来跨越海洋
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.00,0:37:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你现在能听到声音是因为在空气中传播的波
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.00,0:37:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在真空环境下的宇宙，没有空气
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.00,0:37:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以那里也没有声音
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.00,0:37:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但你可以看见我的原因则是因为我被阳光照亮
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.00,0:37:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而阳光则旅行了1.5亿千米
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.00,0:37:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,穿越真空区
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.00,0:37:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么，什么是光
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.00,0:37:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你又是怎样得到一个不在任何物质中的波呢？
Dialogue: 0,0:37:25.00,0:37:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要回答这个问题不仅要解释光是什么
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.00,0:37:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它最终会让我们瞥见
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.00,0:37:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙刚开始的模样
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.00,0:37:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而解决这问题的第一步
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.00,0:37:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,则是一个发现，这个发现挑战了我们
Dialogue: 0,0:37:53.00,0:37:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如何看世界的最基本假设
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.00,0:38:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对我们的眼睛而言，光似乎无处不在
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.00,0:38:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,又稍纵即逝
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.00,0:38:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当我看向这片风景时，似乎并没有什么时间延迟
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.00,0:38:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当我在等待光到达我时，光也没有耽搁
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.00,0:38:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但到了17世纪的末期
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.00,0:38:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的这种感觉被发现是错误的
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.00,0:38:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1672年，丹麦天文学家奥利·罗默到达巴黎
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.00,0:38:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,开始了天文台的工作
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.00,0:38:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并继续观测木星的卫星
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.00,0:38:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,历经十年多的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.00,0:38:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,乔凡尼·卡西尼，该天文台的主任
Dialogue: 0,0:38:52.00,0:38:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,已经编制好了它们每分钟的运行轨道
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.00,0:39:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,已知的木星最里面的卫星木卫一
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.00,0:39:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,会环绕木星做一个周期性的运动
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.00,0:39:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每1.77天转一圈
Dialogue: 0,0:39:27.00,0:39:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就相当于42.5个小时
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.00,0:39:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在，从地球来看，我们可以看见它消失于木星的背后
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.00,0:39:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并绕着它的轨道运行
Dialogue: 0,0:39:37.00,0:39:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,又重新出现在了木星的另一端
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.00,0:39:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但在17世纪60年代的巴黎
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.00,0:39:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,乔凡尼·卡西尼注意到
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.00,0:39:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些星食的时间似乎有所不同
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.00,0:39:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有时候比预测的早，有时候则比预测的晚
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.00,0:40:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在他来巴黎不久后
Dialogue: 0,0:40:01.00,0:40:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,罗默注意到这些波动不是随机发生的
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.00,0:40:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当地球离木星近的时候
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.00,0:40:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所观测到的木卫一就会出现和消失的早一点
Dialogue: 0,0:40:15.00,0:40:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但随着时间的流逝
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.00,0:40:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球绕着太阳的公转轨道转动
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.00,0:40:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使得地球远离了木星
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.00,0:40:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这时日食的出现就比预期晚发生
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.00,0:40:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,罗默知道木卫一环绕木星一周的时间是固定的
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.00,0:40:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他惊人的洞察力促使他意识到这个变化是基于一个事实
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.00,0:40:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那便是光穿过空间需要时间
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.00,0:40:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是它的运作原理...
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.00,0:40:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当地球离木星较远时
Dialogue: 0,0:40:54.00,0:40:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,木卫一日食的出现比预期的晚
Dialogue: 0,0:40:57.00,0:41:01.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为光要更多的时间来走完这段路程
Dialogue: 0,0:41:01.00,0:41:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但当地球离近时它们又出现的早了
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.00,0:41:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为光到达地球的时间减少了
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.00,0:41:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光不是瞬时传播的
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.00,0:41:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它传播的速度是有限的
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.00,0:41:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如今，我们不仅以令人难以置信的精度测量了光速
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.00,0:41:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们还能够看到它的运动过程
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.00,0:41:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这段视频是由麻省理工学院的科学家拍摄的
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.00,0:41:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用的摄像头是专门用来监控极快的化学反应的
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.00,0:41:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的快门速度大约是一皮秒
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.00,0:41:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是百万分之一秒的百万分之一
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.00,0:41:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这个时间内光只能跑三分之一毫米
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.00,0:41:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在，看看当我按下播放键时会发生什么
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.00,0:42:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以看到这是一个激光脉冲
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.00,0:42:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,正穿过一个装满水的瓶子
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.00,0:42:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对我们而言，这个过程稍纵即逝
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.00,0:42:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但摄像机却揭示了这个脉冲到底是如何穿过瓶子的
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.00,0:42:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当脉冲击打水分子时，激光向周围散射和反弹
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.00,0:42:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光速真是快-
Dialogue: 0,0:42:38.00,0:42:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每秒300000公里
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.00,0:42:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以同样的程度放慢的话
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.00,0:42:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一颗子弹就要花整整一年的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.00,0:42:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来穿过这个瓶子的长度
Dialogue: 0,0:42:51.00,0:42:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,知道光速有上限是一回事
Dialogue: 0,0:42:55.00,0:42:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,确确实实看到它的运动又是另外一回事
Dialogue: 0,0:43:02.00,0:43:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,发现光的速度有着重大意义
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.00,0:43:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不单单是因为它对揭示光到底是什么
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.00,0:43:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是至关重要的
Dialogue: 0,0:43:22.00,0:43:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,出生于1831年的夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.00,0:43:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,詹姆斯·克拉克·麦克斯韦将成为19世纪物理学领域的
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.00,0:43:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,重要人物之一
Dialogue: 0,0:43:31.00,0:43:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,【叹息声和掌声】
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.00,0:43:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他在电磁学上的研究
Dialogue: 0,0:43:36.00,0:43:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是那个时代最伟大的成就之一
Dialogue: 0,0:43:43.00,0:43:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里是苏格兰西南部的格伦莱尔
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.00,0:43:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,麦克斯韦的家乡
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.00,0:43:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当他在这里成长时，他就养成了一种对周边事物永不满足的好奇心
Dialogue: 0,0:43:54.00,0:43:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一种理解自然界的渴望
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.00,0:43:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种渴望他从来没有失去过
Dialogue: 0,0:44:11.00,0:44:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,小麦克斯韦似乎很喜欢
Dialogue: 0,0:44:14.00,0:44:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,折磨他的父母和他的保姆
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.00,0:44:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,总是不断询问他们事物是怎样运作的
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.00,0:44:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,“那是个什么呀？”他问道
Dialogue: 0,0:44:23.00,0:44:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果谁冒险给个答案的话
Dialogue: 0,0:44:25.00,0:44:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,小麦克斯只会满足一会儿
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.00,0:44:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,马上他就会问，他们是怎么知道的
Dialogue: 0,0:44:36.00,0:44:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，对一个孩子来说，这没有什么特别不寻常的
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.00,0:44:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但使得麦克斯韦与众不同的是
Dialogue: 0,0:44:42.00,0:44:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,年仅14岁的他
Dialogue: 0,0:44:44.00,0:44:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,却写出了自己的第一篇科学论文
Dialogue: 0,0:44:47.00,0:44:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为太年轻，以至于他家的一个友人
Dialogue: 0,0:44:49.00,0:44:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不得不代表他把这篇论文投到爱丁堡皇家学会
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.00,0:45:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,麦克斯韦是史上最伟大的科学家之一
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.00,0:45:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而正是在这里，麦克斯韦开始了他最重要的工作
Dialogue: 0,0:45:12.00,0:45:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在19世纪60年代
Dialogue: 0,0:45:14.00,0:45:18.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,麦克斯韦导出了一个数学杰作
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.00,0:45:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,证明了电和磁
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.00,0:45:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是同一个事情的不同方面
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.00,0:45:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是他的计算显示了一些别的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:45:29.00,0:45:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很偶然,它们将揭示光的真正本性
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.00,0:45:37.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是麦克斯韦的四个著名方程
Dialogue: 0,0:45:37.00,0:45:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们描述了电场和磁场之间的关系
Dialogue: 0,0:45:43.00,0:45:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,E的旋度
Dialogue: 0,0:45:45.00,0:45:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,等于负的dB除以dt
Dialogue: 0,0:45:49.00,0:45:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,E表示电场，B表示磁场
Dialogue: 0,0:45:52.00,0:45:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,B的旋度除以μ。... ...
Dialogue: 0,0:45:56.00,0:45:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,E的散度等于零... ...
Dialogue: 0,0:45:59.00,0:46:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,... ...等于ε。... ...等于零
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.00,0:46:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,通过一些代数运算和推理
Dialogue: 0,0:46:04.00,0:46:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这四个方程可以结合起来，给出一个单独的方程
Dialogue: 0,0:46:08.00,0:46:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么完成后的形式就像这样...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:11.00,0:46:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们取E的旋度的旋度...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.00,0:46:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,隐藏在这数学公式下的
Dialogue: 0,0:46:16.00,0:46:21.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是连麦克斯韦都没有想到的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.00,0:46:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...ε。...E的梯度2...散度...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.00,0:46:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这个第二项为零
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.00,0:46:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然后我留下E的▽的平方...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:30.00,0:46:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..负的μ。，ε。
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.00,0:46:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,▽的平方E...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:36.00,0:46:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...除以dt的平方
Dialogue: 0,0:46:41.00,0:46:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是波动方程
Dialogue: 0,0:46:44.00,0:46:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它告诉我们电磁场
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.00,0:46:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是如何穿过空间的
Dialogue: 0,0:46:48.00,0:46:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那，最重要的就是这里-
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.00,0:46:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,μ。，ε。 --
Dialogue: 0,0:46:53.00,0:46:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为它与波传播的速度有关
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.00,0:47:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,事实上，速度已经给出了...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.00,0:47:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..它等于1除以根号μ。乘以ε。
Dialogue: 0,0:47:06.00,0:47:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果你把它计算出来，你就会得到...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.00,0:47:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..3乘以10的8次方米每秒
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.00,0:47:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或者3000000千米每秒-
Dialogue: 0,0:47:16.00,0:47:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是光速
Dialogue: 0,0:47:20.00,0:47:24.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果电磁波以光速在运动
Dialogue: 0,0:47:24.00,0:47:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那只能说明一件事
Dialogue: 0,0:47:27.00,0:47:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,麦克斯韦知道这不仅仅是一个巧合
Dialogue: 0,0:47:32.00,0:47:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这意味着光本身就是一种电磁波
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.00,0:47:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,发现光是一种电磁波
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.00,0:47:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,解释了光的一个最令人困惑的属性
Dialogue: 0,0:47:58.00,0:48:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,麦克斯韦的方程告诉我们
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.00,0:48:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光是由穿过空间的电磁波组成的
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.00,0:48:10.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以光只是电和磁的振动
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.00,0:48:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当它们移动的时候就相互激发
Dialogue: 0,0:48:16.00,0:48:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们现在知道,这些电磁波有一个不平凡的属性
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.00,0:48:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们不一定是在什么东西里面的波
Dialogue: 0,0:48:25.00,0:48:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们可以穿过真空
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.00,0:48:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我还记得我第一次学到这个知识的时候是在大二
Dialogue: 0,0:48:49.00,0:48:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在萨里大学物理系33AC21号演讲厅
Dialogue: 0,0:48:55.00,0:48:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,演讲者是奇弗斯博士
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.00,0:48:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我还记得我曾求助于坐在我旁边的朋友
Dialogue: 0,0:48:59.00,0:49:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并且还评论说我认为这个属性太不可思议了
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.00,0:49:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我还记得他当时的反应，觉得我有点怪怪的
Dialogue: 0,0:49:07.00,0:49:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但，事实上，这确实令人难以置信
Dialogue: 0,0:49:12.00,0:49:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就这么几行公式居然能够说清楚光的实质
Dialogue: 0,0:49:19.00,0:49:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且光速有限的这个事实
Dialogue: 0,0:49:22.00,0:49:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使得我们能够做一些别的事情
Dialogue: 0,0:49:26.00,0:49:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使得我们能够看到过去
Dialogue: 0,0:49:32.00,0:49:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看向离你一米远的镜子
Dialogue: 0,0:49:34.00,0:49:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你看见的是六纳秒前的自己
Dialogue: 0,0:49:38.00,0:49:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从地球看到的月亮，是一秒前的月亮
Dialogue: 0,0:49:43.00,0:49:46.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而太阳则是八分钟前的太阳
Dialogue: 0,0:49:46.00,0:49:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你在宇宙中看的越远，你在时间上就看的更早
Dialogue: 0,0:49:52.00,0:49:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光从宇宙中最远的物体传到地球
Dialogue: 0,0:49:56.00,0:50:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要花上几十亿年的功夫
Dialogue: 0,0:50:00.00,0:50:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是有一个波源把我们带到了更远的过去
Dialogue: 0,0:50:04.00,0:50:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们到达了我们能看到的光的极限
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.00,0:50:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1964年，在把一个怪模怪样的号角天线
Dialogue: 0,0:50:19.00,0:50:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从早期用于卫星通信的设计
Dialogue: 0,0:50:22.00,0:50:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,改造成用来做天文观测...的时候
Dialogue: 0,0:50:27.00,0:50:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,..阿尔诺·彭齐亚斯和罗伯特·威尔森
Dialogue: 0,0:50:30.00,0:50:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,开始捕捉到一个他们无法解释的神秘信号
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.00,0:50:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里，我们特意选择了光谱的一部分
Dialogue: 0,0:50:48.00,0:50:49.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个7厘米的波长
Dialogue: 0,0:50:49.00,0:50:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在这个波段，我们本指望没有或几乎没有信号
Dialogue: 0,0:50:53.00,0:50:55.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天空中完全没有这个波段的辐射
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.00,0:51:02.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是，实际发生的状况是，我们发现
Dialogue: 0,0:51:02.00,0:51:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来自各个方向的辐射都进入到我们的天线
Dialogue: 0,0:51:05.00,0:51:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那真是给我们泼了一碗冷水，嗯
Dialogue: 0,0:51:09.00,0:51:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,显然这比我们从银河系的预测要多出几个数量级
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.00,0:51:22.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,起初，他们不予理会，认为这是噪音
Dialogue: 0,0:51:22.00,0:51:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是一些没用的东西，是天线自己生成的
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.00,0:51:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在，我们有了一些怀疑
Dialogue: 0,0:51:29.00,0:51:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为天线的咽喉处一直到操作室都比较暖和
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.00,0:51:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这对鸽子来说是个很有吸引力的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:51:36.00,0:51:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,至少有一对鸽子喜欢停在那，特别是在寒冷的冬天
Dialogue: 0,0:51:41.00,0:51:44.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们并不用担心，因为当我们来时它们就会飞走
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.00,0:51:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,除非它们把天线表面涂上了白色的粘性物质（鸟屎）
Dialogue: 0,0:51:48.00,0:51:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这可能不仅会吸收无线电波还会发射无线电波
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.00,0:51:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这可能就是导致我们结果的部分或全部原因
Dialogue: 0,0:52:02.00,0:52:05.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在清理完天线，和鸽子后-
Dialogue: 0,0:52:05.00,0:52:07.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，对这些鸽子来说这样的结果不太好 -
Dialogue: 0,0:52:07.00,0:52:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,彭齐亚斯和威尔森开始寻找一个天文学的解释
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.00,0:52:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这个信号并不来自我们自己的星系
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.00,0:52:19.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,同样也不是来自其他星系的
Dialogue: 0,0:52:19.00,0:52:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它似乎来自每个地方
Dialogue: 0,0:52:25.00,0:52:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不论是你身处何时，白天或黑夜，冬天或夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:52:28.00,0:52:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种背景辐射在天空中到处都是
Dialogue: 0,0:52:34.00,0:52:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这与银河系或任何其他已知的无线电波源毫无关联
Dialogue: 0,0:52:39.00,0:52:42.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这更像是整个宇宙一直被加热到
Dialogue: 0,0:52:42.00,0:52:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,高于绝对零度三度的温度
Dialogue: 0,0:52:50.00,0:52:54.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以我们得到了惊人的结果
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.00,0:52:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种辐射是来自宇宙深处
Dialogue: 0,0:52:57.00,0:53:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,的某个地方...
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.00,0:53:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...超越了任何我们所知道的
Dialogue: 0,0:53:04.00,0:53:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或我们能想到的无线电来源
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.00,0:53:25.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他们发现的光是如此古老
Dialogue: 0,0:53:25.00,0:53:28.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的波长被拉伸到微波段
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.00,0:53:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,冷的只比绝对零度高一点点
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.00,0:53:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这些光一直在来到地球的途中
Dialogue: 0,0:53:35.00,0:53:38.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,花了几乎整个宇宙年龄的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:53:38.00,0:53:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们不是来自遥远的星系
Dialogue: 0,0:53:40.00,0:53:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们比任何恒星都要年长
Dialogue: 0,0:53:43.00,0:53:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,彭齐亚斯和威尔森发现从宇宙大爆炸的余烬开始
Dialogue: 0,0:53:48.00,0:53:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,整个宇宙就充满着光
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.00,0:54:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它被称为宇宙微波背景辐射
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.00,0:54:15.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当宇宙还只有370000年的时候它被释放
Dialogue: 0,0:54:15.00,0:54:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它呈现给了我们一张宇宙初始阶段的快拍
Dialogue: 0,0:54:24.00,0:54:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是这张
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.00,0:54:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最新的宇宙微波背景的图像
Dialogue: 0,0:54:29.00,0:54:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由普朗克卫星获得，并于2013年初发表
Dialogue: 0,0:54:33.00,0:54:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不同的颜色表示的是在早期宇宙温度的波动
Dialogue: 0,0:54:39.00,0:54:41.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们所包含的信息
Dialogue: 0,0:54:41.00,0:54:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这对宇宙学家来说是无价的
Dialogue: 0,0:54:46.00,0:54:51.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,物质聚集在一起引起温度的微小变化
Dialogue: 0,0:54:51.00,0:54:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最终使它们成为了恒星和星系
Dialogue: 0,0:54:57.00,0:55:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这个图像 真正引人注目的
Dialogue: 0,0:55:00.00,0:55:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并不仅仅只是这个来自早期宇宙的光
Dialogue: 0,0:55:03.00,0:55:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而是这个第一束光的初始模样
Dialogue: 0,0:55:31.00,0:55:34.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从这些光诞生的最初时刻
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.00,0:55:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙是一个火球样的热的等离子体
Dialogue: 0,0:55:39.00,0:55:43.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,困住光，不让它移动
Dialogue: 0,0:55:45.00,0:55:50.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然后，当宇宙冷却后，等离子体凝聚
Dialogue: 0,0:55:50.00,0:55:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,形成第一批原子...
Dialogue: 0,0:55:58.00,0:56:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...和第一束光
Dialogue: 0,0:56:00.00,0:56:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这束光将成为宇宙微波背景
Dialogue: 0,0:56:04.00,0:56:08.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,被释放到宇宙去
Dialogue: 0,0:56:22.00,0:56:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要想表达这个成就是有多么惊人是有点困难的
Dialogue: 0,0:56:27.00,0:56:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从我们自己的小行星，围绕着一个不起眼的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.00,0:56:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们就能联系到宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:56:35.00,0:56:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并通过光来尽我们所能地看得更远
Dialogue: 0,0:56:55.00,0:56:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙微波背景的发现
Dialogue: 0,0:56:58.00,0:57:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,似乎完成了我们的宇宙图像
Dialogue: 0,0:57:03.00,0:57:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也是人类利用光来
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.00,0:57:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,探索宇宙的最后篇章
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.00,0:57:16.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,理解光的本质让我们照亮了我们的世界
Dialogue: 0,0:57:16.00,0:57:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们从空间深处和时间的开始处捕捉到了它
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.00,0:57:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在最小尺度上，光使得我们
Dialogue: 0,0:57:23.00,0:57:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,发现了生物的微观结构
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.00,0:57:27.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而在最大尺度上
Dialogue: 0,0:57:27.00,0:57:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它向我们展示了我们在宇宙中所处的位置
Dialogue: 0,0:57:29.00,0:57:32.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并告诉了我们关于恒星的故事
Dialogue: 0,0:57:32.00,0:57:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,实际上我们所知道的有关宇宙的一切
Dialogue: 0,0:57:35.00,0:57:39.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们知道，是因为它是被光照亮的
Dialogue: 0,0:57:46.00,0:57:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是，正当光似乎会引导我们
Dialogue: 0,0:57:48.00,0:57:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,完整理解万物的时候...
Dialogue: 0,0:57:54.00,0:57:56.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,...在最近30年
Dialogue: 0,0:57:56.00,0:57:59.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它向我们展示了令人头疼的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:58:00.00,0:58:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那便是绝大多数的宇宙根本看不见
Dialogue: 0,0:58:11.00,0:58:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,远非一个光的宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:58:14.00,0:58:17.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们大多数都隐藏在黑暗中
Dialogue: 0,0:58:22.00,0:58:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,下一期
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.00,0:58:26.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,科学家是如何意识到
Dialogue: 0,0:58:26.00,0:58:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,超过99%的宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:58:29.00,0:58:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,藏在阴影中
Dialogue: 0,0:58:33.00,0:58:36.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,又是如何开展非凡的探索
Dialogue: 0,0:58:36.00,0:58:40.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,来揭示隐藏在黑暗中的秘密
Dialogue: 0,0:58:43.00,0:58:45.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,无论你是想要深入的了解光
Dialogue: 0,0:58:45.00,0:58:48.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还是想要探索黑暗的神秘之处
Dialogue: 0,0:58:48.00,0:58:52.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,让英国开放大学 来启发你，请到
Dialogue: 0,0:58:55.00,0:58:58.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并点击开放大学的链接
